Instead of a traditional database, Claude Code treats the File System as Memory, using Markdown files and a trio of specialized sub-agents to maintain context. Here is a breakdown of how this three-layer memory architecture works.

1. Auto-Memory: The Long-Term Repository
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Claude Code stores long-term memory at ~/.claude/projects/<sanitized-git-root>/memory/. By resolving the canonical git root, it ensures that all worktrees of the same repository share a single memory source.

The Anatomy of a Memory File
Each memory entry is a standalone .md file. These files use a strict frontmatter format to define the entry:

Name & Description
Type: Categorized as user, feedback, project, or reference.
The Index: A file named MEMORY.md acts as a 200-line index. It doesn’t store the actual content but serves as a map. If the index exceeds 200 lines, older entries are truncated.
The Maintenance Sub-agent
After every conversation round, the system forks a specialized sub-agent. This agent’s sole job is to extract new insights from the latest messages. To ensure safety, its tools are heavily restricted: it can only use read-only Bash commands and file-system tools (Edit/Write) limited strictly to the memory directory.

2. Agent-Tool Memory: Modular Knowledge
Beyond the primary “Auto-Memory,” there is Agent-Tool Memory. This is reserved for custom sub-agents defined by the user in .claude/agents/.


If you define a security-reviewer agent, it gets its own namespace: .claude/agent-memory/security-reviewer/. This allows specialized agents to accumulate domain-specific experience (like security patterns) without polluting the main project memory. These memories follow a specific scope defined in their frontmatter—ranging from User-level (global) to Project-level (repo-specific) or Local (machine-specific).

3. The Retrieval Mechanism: The “Small Model” Filter
Claude Code does not cram every memory file into the context window. Instead, it uses a lightweight, structured retrieval process:

Scanning: It scans the frontmatter of all files in the memory directory to generate a list of available insights.
Reasoning: It sends this list to Claude 3.5 Sonnet with a strict JSON schema and a 256-token limit. The model identifies up to 5 “definitively useful” files.
Attachment: The contents of these 5 files are injected into the current user message as a <system-reminder>, which the system calls an Attachment.
Using Sonnet for this “lookup” phase is a deliberate choice. While a smaller model could do it, the system relies on Sonnet’s reasoning to judge relevance, while keeping costs low through extreme output constraints.

4. Session Memory & Compaction: Managing the Context Window
To prevent “context explosion,” Claude Code runs a parallel system for short-term session tracking.

Session Notes
This isn’t a post-hoc summary; it’s a living document. Once the session hits 10,000 tokens, a sub-agent begins updating a Markdown template that tracks progress, decisions, and critical context. These notes are updated every 5,000 new tokens, provided at least three tool calls have occurred.

Compaction: The Safety Valve
When the context window (200k tokens) nears its limit (typically around 180k–190k tokens), the Compaction mechanism triggers:

Path A: If “Session Notes” exist, the system uses them as the summary, keeps the most recent messages, and flushes the rest.
Path B: If no notes are available, it falls back to the traditional method of calling the API to generate a fresh summary.
5. Security: The Trade-off of File-Based Memory
The beauty of this design is its debuggability. You can diff your memory files just like code. However, "File as Memory" requires rigorous path validation. The system must explicitly reject relative paths, UNC paths, and null bytes to prevent a rogue sub-agent from escaping its sandbox and writing to sensitive areas of the OS.

Final Thoughts
Claude Code proves that you don’t need a complex vector infrastructure to build a high-functioning agent. By combining Markdown storage, strict sub-agent permissions, and hierarchical summarization, they’ve built a system that is transparent, portable, and remarkably robust. It’s a “boring” architecture in the best way possible — prioritizing reliability over hype.



